        Source questionnaire available from NEF Consulting downloads page.
      </holdings>
    </citation>

    <stdyInfo>
      <subject>
        <keyword>social capital</keyword>
        <keyword>quality of life</keyword>
        <keyword>community safety</keyword>
        <keyword>civic participation</keyword>
        <keyword>interpersonal trust</keyword>
        <keyword>institutional trust</keyword>
        <keyword>social reciprocity</keyword>
        <keyword>self-efficacy</keyword>
        <keyword>bridging social capital</keyword>
        <keyword>bonding social capital</keyword>
        <keyword>neighbourhood improvement</keyword>
        <topcClas>Impact Assessment</topcClas>
        <topcClas>Template</topcClas>
      </subject>
      <abstract>
        <xhtml:p xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          To make the survey in the <xhtml:em>Prove It!</xhtml:em> Toolkit as simple to administer as possible we have chosen a Core List of the most powerful indicators of a project's impact on social capital and quality of life. For each indicator there are between one and three simple questions to be asked of project participants and members of non-project-participating members of the wider community.
        </xhtml:p>
        <xhtml:p xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          This core list of suggested indicators relates to the potential effects of a project on:
        </xhtml:p>
        <xhtml:ol xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          <xhtml:li>Frequency of use of the new space or facility</xhtml:li>
          <xhtml:li>Attractiveness of the neighbourhood</xhtml:li>
          <xhtml:li>Levels of community safety</xhtml:li>
          <xhtml:li>People's inclusion, involvement and trust in local decision-making processes</xhtml:li>
          <xhtml:li>People's networks and contacts:
            <xhtml:ul>
              <xhtml:li>for achieving change</xhtml:li>
              <xhtml:li>for feeling connected to a community</xhtml:li>
              <xhtml:li>in case of a need for help</xhtml:li>
            </xhtml:ul>
          </xhtml:li>
        </xhtml:ol>
        <xhtml:p xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          To these, you, as project manager, may add further indicators that will be specific to your project. In addition there are some readymade demographic questions that can help you to establish and report which specific groups of people have been involved or affected by your project.
        </xhtml:p>
        <xhtml:p xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          The current wording and layout of the questions represents how a simple social capital survey could be conducted. We acknowledge that although many overriding aims are similar, every project is different and we have set it up in a way that allows the individual wording of each question to be altered to suit local circumstance.
        </xhtml:p>
      </abstract>
      <sumDscr>
        <anlyUnit>Individuals</anlyUnit>
        <universe>Participants in community programmes and social enterprise beneficiaries</universe>
        <dataKind>Survey Data</dataKind>
      </sumDscr>
    </stdyInfo>
  </stdyDscr>

